0.body: Pyr is a programming language based on Python .
0.title: Overview

1.body: Static type checking Can be interpreted Can be compiled into a native object file (using LLVM )
1.title: Features

10.body: if evaluates its condition and if it's truthy, it executes its body. if 34 < 56: print "34 is less than 56\n" # Executes this line
10.title: if

11.body:
else executes its body if the previous if's condition is falsy. if 100 < 50: print "100 is less than 50
" # Skips this line
else: print "100 is greater than 50
" # Executes this line else can also be continued with another if: if 100 < 50: print "100 is less than 50
" # Skips this line
else if 100 > 50: print "100 is greater than 50
" # Executes this line
else: print "100 is equal to 50
" # Skips this line
11.title: else

12.body:
while will execute its body until the condition is falsy. i = 0
while i < 10: # Executes its body 10 times print i + "\n" i += 1
12.title: while

13.body:
and with the same type of operands will return the left value if either is falsy and will return the right value if both are truthy. and with different types of operands will return false if either is falsy and will true if both are truthy. and will short circuit if left hand side is falsy. 10 > 2 and 10 < 20 # result is true
"hello" and "world" # result is "world"
123 and "" # result is false
13.title: and

14.body:
or with the same type of operands will return the left value if it is truthy otherwise it will return the right hand side. or with different types of operands will return true if either is truthy and will return false if both are falsy. or will short circuit if left hand side is truthy. 10 > 2 or 10 < 20 # result is true
"hello" or "world" # result is "hello"
123 or "" # result is true
14.title: or

15.body: func defines a function. For more information, see Functions . func square(x: int): print x * x
15.title: func

16.body: Arithmetic Addition Subtraction Multiplication Division Negation Exponent Modulo / Remainder
16.title: Arithmetic

17.body: + with integers will add the numbers together. 1 + 2 # result is 3 + with strings is concatenation. "Hello, " + "World!" # result is "Hello, World!"
17.title: Addition

18.body: - will subtract the first number with the second. 1 - 2 # result is -1
18.title: Subtraction

19.body: * with integers will multiply the numbers together. 1 * 2 # result is 2 * between strings and integers is string repetition. "Hello" * 3 # result is "HelloHelloHello"
19.title: Multiplication

2.body:
Pyr is written in Rust . To compile Pyr you need to have a Rust compiler and LLVM version 14.0.x. To compile Pyr: cargo build --release To interpret a Pyr program: pyr run foo.pyr To compile a Pyr program: pyr compile foo.pyr
clang foo.o -o foo
2.title: Quick Start

20.body: / with integers will divide the first number by the second. 30 / 5 # result is 6
20.title: Division

21.body:
- will either make its right hand side negative or positive. ! will return true if its right hand side is falsy, and false if it is truthy. -1 # result is -1
!true # result is 0 For more information about truthiness and falsiness, see Truthiness .
21.title: Negation

22.body: ^ will multiply its left hand side by itself the number of times on the right hand side. 2 ^ 3 # result is 8
22.title: Exponent

23.body:
% will return the remainder of its left hand side subtracted by its right hand side multiple times until it is less than its original value. 30 % 5 # result is 0
4 % 3 # result is 1
12 % 5 # result is 2
23.title: Modulo / Remainder

24.body: Comparison Less Than Greater Than Less Than or Equal Greater Than or Equal Equal Not Equal And and Or
24.title: Comparison

25.body: < will return true if its left hand side is less than its right hand side. 1 < 2 # result is true
25.title: Less Than

26.body: > will return true if its left hand side is greater than its right hand side. 1 > 2 # result is false
26.title: Greater Than

27.body: <= will return true if its left hand side is less than or equal to its right hand side. 2 <= 2 # result is true
27.title: Less Than or Equal

28.body: >= will return true if its left hand side is greater than or equal to its right hand side. 2 >= 2 # result is true
28.title: Greater Than or Equal

29.body:
== will return true if its left hand side is equal to its right hand side. 1 == 2 # result is false
"Hello" == "Hello" # result is true
"Hello" == "World" # result is false
29.title: Equal

3.body: Pyr is under the license of Apache-2.0 .
3.title: License

30.body:
!= will return true if its left hand side is not equal to its right hand side. 1 != 2 # result is true
"Hello" != "Hello" # result is false
"Hello" != "World" # result is true
30.title: Not Equal

33.body:
An integer is truthy if it is equal to 1. !!0 # result is false
!!1 # result is true
!!2 # result is false
33.title: Integers

34.body:
A string is truthy if it is not empty. !!"" # result is false
!!"Hello" # result is true
34.title: String

36.body: Declaration and assignment in Pyr use the same syntax. foo = "bar" To access a variable, use the following syntax. print var_name # prints "bar"
36.title: Variable

37.body:
Functions in Pyr are defined with the func keyword. Function arguments are explicitly typed , and are separated by commas. func foo(a: int, b: int) -> int: print a + b + "\n" To call a function, simply use the function name and parentheses with the arguments. foo(1, 2) # prints 3 Functions and variables have different scopes. So you can have both a variable named foo and a function named foo. foo = "bar"
func foo(): print foo + "\n" foo() # prints "bar"
foo = "baz"
foo() # prints "baz" Functions can also return a value. func sum_of_squares(a: int, b: int) -> int: return a ^ 2 + b ^ 2 print sum_of_squares(2, 3) # prints 9 To overload a function, you can define a function with the same name and different arguments. func foo(a: int) -> string: return "int" func foo(a: string) -> string: return "string" foo(1) # returns "int"
foo("foo") # returns "string"
37.title: Functions

38.body:
Comments in Pyr starts with a # and go to the end of the line. # This is a comment # print "Hello World"
# ^ Skipped Multiline comments are currently not supported but are planned.
38.title: Comments

4.body: Pyr currently supports the following literals: Literals Integer Boolean String
4.title: Literals

5.body: Integers in Pyr are 64 bit signed integers. 123 Type: int
5.title: Integer

6.body:
Booleans in Pyr are secretly integers with true as 1 and false as 0. true # returns 1
false # returns 0 Type: int
6.title: Boolean

7.body:
Strings in Pyr are delimited by double quotes. For escaping things like double quotes, you can use a backslash. Multiline strings are also supported. "Hello, World!"
"Newlines\n" Type: string
7.title: String

8.body: Keywords in Pyr are as follows: Keywords print if else while and or func
8.title: Keywords

9.body: print prints its right hand side to stdout. Currently, print is a keyword, but later on it will be a function. print does not automatically add a newline. print "Hello, World\n" # prints Hello, World
9.title: print
